<section class="about reveal" id="about">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="section-head">
      <span class="index">01 — About</span>
      <h2>A philosopher of the in-between</h2>
      <span class="rule"></span>
    </div>

    <div class="grid">
      <p class="lead">
        How might we live well alongside the more-than-human world — its
        creatures, its plants, its technologies, its weather?
      </p>

      <div class="body">
        <p>
          I work in the continental tradition, at the meeting point of environment
          and technology. I'm a Lecturer II in the Department of Philosophy at the
          University of Texas Rio Grande Valley, and earned my Ph.D. at the
          University of Georgia in 2022.
        </p>
        <p>
          Drawing on new materialisms and material feminisms — Karen Barad, Donna
          Haraway, Rosi Braidotti — I ask how humans and nonhumans are entangled,
          and what we owe one another. My work develops an environmental ethic of
          gratitude, reciprocity, and open-ended curiosity, and argues that
          nonhumans, too, can be knowers and agents in shared worlds of flourishing.
        </p>
        <p>
          My first book, <i>Toward an Environmental Ethic of Surprise: Adventures
          in Attention</i> (2025), follows that thread into a practice of attention —
          staying open to wonder as a way of living well amid ecological crisis.
        </p>

        <p class="dialectic-note">
          This page lives in two moods. <b>Physis</b> <span lang="grc">(φύσις)</span>
          — the self-arising, the world as it grows of its own accord. <b>Technê</b>
          <span lang="grc">(τέχνη)</span> — the bringing-forth, the world as we make
          and remake it. My work thinks the space between them; the toggle in the
          corner lets you read the page under either aspect.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
